Some of the plays are actually instances of a player fumbling twice.

It looks like the rest are actually errors in the source data that we won't fix. Namely, a single fumble occurs, but it is simultaneously reported as both a forced fumble and *not* a forced fumble. So either the data is in error, or there is more nuance that isn't captured by the data.

The plays where fumbling happened twice turn out to be cool candidates to watch! http://fantasy.burntsushi.net/query?refresh=0&my_players=0&limit=500&sort=-game_date&sort=-play_id&play_fumbles_tot__ge=2&entity=play

Actually I read the documentation and the code again and I think I kind of understand where I went wrong. Originally I thought pageReset would be used upon any update to the table but it looks like you don't use it if the filters the table knows about aren't changed (because it would then be a pager triggered update using the same set of filters). Since I don't use the filter widget or bind my custom filters to the table, it probably doesn't know my changes are actually filter-triggered changes (since I call pagerUpdate to update my table) and thus doesn't reset my page back to the first.

I ended up going with the work around of having changes on my custom filters trigger a click on '.first' which is the first page button on the pager when that button is not disabled (already on page 1) and trigger pagerUpdate otherwise.

if($('.first').hasClass('disabled')) {
        $('#users-table').trigger('pagerUpdate');
    }
    else {
        $('.first').trigger('click');
    }

In fact, that page initializes tablesorter like 4 times... can you remove all that extra code? Including, this bit - it's not even valid javascript:

```js
	$(function(){	
	filter_placeholder : {
  search : '', // any default search inputs including the datepicker comparison
  from   : 'Date from...', // datepicker range "from" placeholder
  to     : 'Date to...'  // datepicker range "to" placeholder
}
```

